EROI is a unitless ratio, defined as the ratio of the gross energy output over the operating lifetime for an energy supply system, and the sum of the energy for manufacture, construction, operation and maintenance, decommissioning and disposal/recycling over the system’s project life-cycle (Murphy et al. 2011, Eq. 1). Murphy and Hall (2010) state that ‘EROI is the ratio of how much energy is gained from an energy production process compared to how much of that energy (or its equivalent from some other source) is required to extract, grow, etc., a new unit of the energy in question.’ EPBT is the length of time, in years, for a PV system to generate the same amount of energy (in terms of primary energy equivalent) that was used to produce the system itself (Frischknecht et al. 2016, Sect. 3.4.2). The energy invested (embodied energy) is established by LCA. For a PV system, this is the same as the cumulative energy demand (CED). However, the CED of PV electricity differs markedly depending on whether the ‘energy harvested’ or the ‘energy harvestable’ concept is applied (see “Output Energy form Equivalence in the Context of PV NEA” section). Energy investment and output can be expressed in different forms depending on the goal of the study, as discussed in detail in “Equivalence of Investment and Output Energy Forms” section.1EROI=EoutEinv\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
